niet ofte ul heeft voor nu ontfangen 3 packen van brugge AN36
het welke sonder tijt verlies p: tasen hetrewaerts moet gesonden word

In Antwarp uno1016
London Bickering & Robinson
th
S. I have recd. in due time yd of 4: past, wherin I observe that the
acompt of cloth proves to content & that you intend to be where cloth
is bought in a short time, wherefore do send here inclosed pattars to
provide 12 cloathes to each pattarnes, one from 3 st: ayd to 3:6 raw
besides 12 clouthes to each pattarne one, from 4 s te 4 s 6 pence
a ydraw which will be 24 cloathes, 1z one pack, & each pack
to be well rapped with att least 3 white manchester bayes to be
sent to suill & shipt off there in an english vessel, butt above all
lett the goods be curiously drest alloves, not onely neare the lists
butt all the cloth over & neatty handled & toilletted, lett also yd fre ind
cntt pattarnes & make a prottarne book of each pack & be sent mee
as soone as don because wee often sell the goods by the pattarnes before
arrivall, so shall leave the rest to yd experiency whilst nextweek sheve
ship off here aboard Adriaen de haes for london a pack of tykes
ass well assorted & as good are as to be had for mony for atryall, for
legaturen have ordered a few to be provided according to yd order & when
you finde any incorigment to either, have butt liberly to command
I confess you have reason to complaine of the lead, whoever I didittfor
the best, because in case I had laid itteipp, itt should have cost more
laboridge, & saw plainly that itt would not to better, because I have been
obliged to pay talles, which if itt should have beon for my owne acctt
should have eschaped & advanced onely by that neave ƒ30: besides brolidge
which those that use to make itt their bussynes & fell for their owne
acctt to advance & haveing perused that, was t he cause to my sister
in lace did give orders for more, so hope you will pass that over
& that the now desired cloathes will make amends, for I can
not see goods lye by, & thought that com be so estimed & risen yett never thelet
here is yett such shantities oflead that itt is sod still for 23 staydid yd
Condt these i2 pattarnes serves to provide

London George Cole
In Antwarp 1 march ie
th
Sr. I have before mee yd of 7 & 11 past. yd bill for £100: 18 duels discher
& past to acctt. of the estate of JV. inclosed p bill of £80 on m.
Henry maynard att 10 dayes sich which please to pass to same accomd
att 35:7 here also you have the needfull accompts of sale which
please to peruse & finding any thing to yd freinds or my preuidice & note
accordingly & you will oblige mee whilst Ishall expect to heare of
the £80 more mentionsd for which never was any order or procure
given to compose & so remaine with kinde salues
InAntwarp 1 march
London will Scawens
th
S. my last to you was on the 22: past sence recd. yd of 11 ditto & seeng you
are not incorridged to have any more tijkes shall send non, thought me
thinckes they ought to be worth as much, n'ay more then mony returned
p ex att time whoever soas you please inclosed a bill of mine on
mr. Henry Maynard att 10 dayes sight for £40 att 35:7 for yd acctt
which please to note accordingly: I have advise from m. Coots
of Bruges that there is a pack of callicoes of others seased, where
fore advise mee not to medd le with any, yett agreat while, so that
I am att astand whoever I shall want cattons, & because wee might
40 securer wee kan pack 25 or 30 butt in one bale and in each ship
butt one bale & gett itt over att a longer rumim other wise I see no
remedie so then please to buy att the east india sale 200 sulempores
of 12: 6or 13 to be dyed as the least you sent butt I could wishh there
avere amonghst them 50 of a finer sort how they must be dyed shall
advised p. next buy also 50 browne salempores off the same qualetie
besides 60 or 70 of d„ zatt 29:6 & if them were browne itt should be
the better for our peonle loves more the browne then white ned goods
which serves to governo from
In Antwap 1 march
London Henry Maynard
S my last to you was on the 22: past sence non from you this then to
scary the inclosed bill for £250: ot att 3 dayes sight on Richd floot
which please to gett accepted & p: dutt due time cost mee 35:7 which
stinck is better then to allow 35:5 a6 att 2 uso, & haveing some monge
to remitt, die itt in one bill because, I could not finde itt bter wise
where fore I hope you will not be offended, that I draw on you to
pay out of that, valew £80: to mr George cole & £40 to mr. William
scawen, both att 10 dayes sight att 35:7, so please to noteaccordingey
on yd scuritt & in hopes to make use of some mony for y my suply
without loss have been bold to negotiate, or draw on you att 2uso £i0s
odd mony, the iust some not beeng yett mentioned & thetime
beeng past that our letters go off thinck they will demand my bill
p: next itt beeng for the valew of henrij van horenbeeke, whichI
desire you to accept & pass to my acctt & when dew redraw on mee
in case not prevented by remises: our trade comes in also monyss
where fore hope to be aremitting more p very first whiest
I remaine with kinde saluts
